$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}h(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}\dfrac{\sqrt{x+26}-5}{x+1}\qquad\gray{\text{This is the rule for }x\neq -1}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}\dfrac{\sqrt{x+26}-5}{x+1}\cdot\dfrac{\sqrt{x+26}+5}{\sqrt{x+26}+5}\qquad\gray{\text{Rationalize}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}\dfrac{x+26-5^2}{(x+1)(\sqrt{x+26}+5)}\qquad\gray{\text{Simplify}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}\dfrac{\cancel{x+1}}{\cancel{(x+1)}(\sqrt{x+26}+5)}\qquad\gray{\text{Cancel common factors}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}\dfrac{1}{(\sqrt{x+26}+5)}
\\\\
&\small\text{(This is allowed because }x\neq -1)
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{-1+26}+5}\qquad\gray{\text{Direct substitution}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{10}
\end{align}$

We obtained that if we set $k=\dfrac{1}{10}$, then $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1}h(x)=h(-1)$, which makes $h$ continuous at $x=-1$.

Since we already saw that $h$ is continuous for any other $x>-26$, we can determine that it's continuous for all $x>-26$.

